{
  "document_id": "prov-27",
  "title": "Proverbs 27",
  "type": "study-bible",
  "translation": "Oxford",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-heading-28",
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "28"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-2",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 2,
      "text": "Let another praise you, and not your own mouth— a stranger, and not your own lips."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-2",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "27.2 : , terms used negatively to describe the “strange” woman in chs 1–9; see 2.16n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 2,
      "verse_end": 2
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-3",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 3,
      "text": "A stone is heavy, and sand is weighty, but a fool's provocation is heavier than both."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-4",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 4,
      "text": "Wrath is cruel, anger is overwhelming, but who is able to stand before jealousy?"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-3",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "3–4 : , see 12.16n.; cf. Sir 22.14–15. Proverbs always portrays as destructive (e.g., 6.34–35; 14.30; cf. Song 8.6–7).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 3,
      "verse_end": 4
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-5",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 5,
      "text": "Better is open rebuke than hidden love."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-6",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 6,
      "text": "Well meant are the wounds a friend inflicts, but profuse are the kisses of an enemy."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-4",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "5–6 : , see 1.23n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 5,
      "verse_end": 6
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-7",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 7,
      "text": "The sated appetite spurns honey, but to a ravenous appetite even the bitter is sweet."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-5",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "7 : , see 5.3n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 7,
      "verse_end": 7
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-8",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 8,
      "text": "Like a bird that strays from its nest is one who strays from home."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-9",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 9,
      "text": "Perfume and incense make the heart glad, but the soul is torn by trouble."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-6",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "9b : Sweetness of a friend's advice (see textual note ), see 16.21; 24.13–14.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 9,
      "verse_end": 9
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-10",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 10,
      "text": "Do not forsake your friend or the friend of your parent; do not go to the house of your kindred in the day of your calamity. Better is a neighbor who is nearby than kindred who are far away."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-7",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "10 : Friendship in times of crisis, see 17.17; 18.24.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 10,
      "verse_end": 10
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-11",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 11,
      "text": "Be wise, my child, and make my heart glad, so that I may answer whoever reproaches me."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-8",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "11 : See 23.15–16n.; cf. Ps 127.4–5; Sir 30.2.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 11,
      "verse_end": 11
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-12",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 12,
      "text": "The clever see danger and hide; but the simple go on, and suffer for it."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-9",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "12 : See 22.3.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 12,
      "verse_end": 12
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-13",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 13,
      "text": "Take the garment of one who has given surety for a stranger; seize the pledge given as surety for foreigners."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-10",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "13 : , see 6.1–5n.; cf. 20.16.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 13,
      "verse_end": 13
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-14",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 14,
      "text": "Whoever blesses a neighbor with a loud voice, rising early in the morning, will be counted as cursing."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-15",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 15,
      "text": "A continual dripping on a rainy day and a contentious wife are alike;"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-16",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 16,
      "text": "to restrain her is to restrain the wind or to grasp oil in the right hand."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-11",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "15–16 : , see 19.13–14n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 15,
      "verse_end": 16
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-17",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 17,
      "text": "Iron sharpens iron, and one person sharpens the wits of another."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-18",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 18,
      "text": "Anyone who tends a fig tree will eat its fruit, and anyone who takes care of a master will be honored."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-12",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "18 : , see 1.31–33n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 18,
      "verse_end": 18
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-19",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 19,
      "text": "Just as water reflects the face, so one human heart reflects another."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-20",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 20,
      "text": "Sheol and Abaddon are never satisfied, and human eyes are never satisfied."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-13",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "20 : , see 1.12n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 20,
      "verse_end": 20
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-21",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 21,
      "text": "The crucible is for silver, and the furnace is for gold, so a person is tested by being praised."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-22",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 22,
      "text": "Crush a fool in a mortar with a pestle along with crushed grain, but the folly will not be driven out."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-14",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "21–22 : See 17.3n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 21,
      "verse_end": 22
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-23",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 23,
      "text": "Know well the condition of your flocks, and give attention to your herds;"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-24",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 24,
      "text": "for riches do not last forever, nor a crown for all generations."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-25",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 25,
      "text": "When the grass is gone, and new growth appears, and the herbage of the mountains is gathered,"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-26",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 26,
      "text": "the lambs will provide your clothing, and the goats the price of a field;"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-27",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 27,
      "text": "there will be enough goats’ milk for your food, for the food of your household and nourishment for your servant-girls."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-1",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "25.1–29.27: These are other proverbs of Solomon that the officials of King Hezekiah of Judah copied.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 27
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-27-h1kj-15",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "23–27 : A concluding poem (cf. 24.30–34) that elaborates on 12.10.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 27
      },
      "verse_start": 23,
      "verse_end": 27
    }
  ]
}